('chunk_4d6ad9e1da96715443','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Why Theatre History Matters','**Definition.** Studying theatre history means understanding **how theatre developed across time and place** — its forms, spaces, and conventions.

**Why it matters.** History gives us context: it explains where modern conventions (scripts, tragedy/comedy, the very idea of an "audience") came from, and it helps us appreciate and analyse today''s theatre more deeply. This is the **Orientation in space and time** global context in action.

**Analogy.** Watching theatre without knowing its history is like hearing the end of a story with no beginning — you enjoy it, but you miss why it matters.

**Common misconception.** *"Old theatre is irrelevant to plays and shows today."*
**Correction.** Modern theatre is built on ancient foundations — Greek structure, genres, and stagecraft still shape musicals, films, and plays now.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Describe* one reason theatre history helps us appreciate modern performance.
- *Evaluate* whether knowing a play''s history changes how we understand it.

---','{"concept":1,"why":3,"theatre":8,"history":6,"matters":3,"definition":1,"studying":1,"means":1,"understanding":1,"how":2,"developed":1,"across":1,"time":2,"and":8,"place":1,"its":2,"forms":1,"spaces":1,"conventions":2,"gives":1,"context":2,"explains":1,"where":1,"modern":3,"scripts":1,"tragedy":1,"comedy":1,"the":3,"very":1,"idea":1,"audience":1,"came":1,"from":1,"helps":2,"appreciate":2,"analyse":1,"today":2,"more":1,"deeply":1,"this":1,"orientation":1,"space":1,"global":1,"action":1,"analogy":1,"watching":1,"without":1,"knowing":2,"like":1,"hearing":1,"end":1,"story":1,"with":1,"beginning":1,"you":2,"enjoy":1,"but":1,"miss":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"old":1,"irrelevant":1,"plays":2,"shows":1,"correction":1,"built":1,"ancient":1,"foundations":1,"greek":1,"structure":1,"genres":1,"stagecraft":1,"still":1,"shape":1,"musicals":1,"films":1,"now":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"describe":1,"one":1,"reason":1,"performance":1,"evaluate":1,"whether":1,"play":1,"changes":1,"understand":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_77b549dd20db215fb8','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Ancient Greek Theatre (c. 6th–4th century BCE)','**Definition.** The earliest well-documented Western theatre, born in **Athens** from **religious festivals honouring Dionysus** (god of wine, fertility, and theatre), especially the **City Dionysia**. Plays were performed as **competitions**.

**Conventions and features.**
- **Performance space — the amphitheatre:** a large **open-air**, semi-circular theatre built into a hillside for excellent natural acoustics (e.g., the Theatre of Dionysus in Athens; the Theatre of Epidaurus). Key areas: the **orchestra** (round "dancing place" where the chorus performed), the **skene** (backdrop building — origin of the word "scene"), and the **theatron** (seating).
- **The chorus:** a **group of performers who sang, chanted, and moved together**, commenting on the action, representing the community, and guiding the audience''s response. It was central, not decorative.
- **Masks:** actors wore large **masks** to show character type and emotion and to help project the voice; a few male actors played all roles, changing masks to switch characters.
- **Genres — tragedy and comedy:** **Tragedy** dealt with serious themes, fate, and downfall; **comedy** was humorous and often satirised politics and society.

**Major playwrights (accurate).**
| Playwright | Type | Notable works |
|------------|------|---------------|
| **Aeschylus** | Tragedy (earliest of the three great tragedians; added the **second actor**) | *The Oresteia*, *Prometheus Bound* |
| **Sophocles** | Tragedy (added the **third actor** and scene-painting) | *Antigone*, *Oedipus Rex*, *Electra* |
| **Euripides** | Tragedy (more realistic, questioning characters) | *Medea*, *The Bacchae* |
| **Aristophanes** | **Comedy** ("Old Comedy," political satire) | *Lysistrata*, *The Frogs*, *The Clouds* |

**Analogy.** The Greek chorus is like a live "commentary track" *and* the crowd''s voice rolled into one — telling us how to feel and filling in the story.

**Why it matters.** Greek theatre gave us tragedy and comedy, the script, the actor, and much of dramatic structure.

**Common misconceptions.**
- *"Ancient Greek theatre had elaborate, realistic sets."* **Correction:** Staging was **minimal** — the *skene* and a few devices; meaning came from language, chorus, masks, and the audience''s imagination, not detailed scenery.
- *"The chorus was just background decoration."* **Correction:** The chorus was a **central storytelling device** — it narrated, judged, questioned characters, and voiced the community.
- *"Women performed on the Greek stage."* **Correction:** In Athens, performers were **male**; men played female roles using masks.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* three features of an ancient Greek amphitheatre.
- *Describe* the role of the chorus in Greek theatre.
- *Analyse* why masks were useful in a large open-air theatre.
- *Interpret* why theatre was linked to the festivals of Dionysus.

---','{"concept":1,"ancient":3,"greek":7,"theatre":11,"6th":1,"4th":1,"century":1,"bce":1,"definition":1,"the":36,"earliest":2,"well":1,"documented":1,"western":1,"born":1,"athens":3,"from":2,"religious":1,"festivals":2,"honouring":1,"dionysus":3,"god":1,"wine":1,"fertility":1,"and":19,"especially":1,"city":1,"dionysia":1,"plays":1,"were":3,"performed":3,"competitions":1,"conventions":1,"features":2,"performance":1,"space":1,"amphitheatre":2,"large":3,"open":2,"air":2,"semi":1,"circular":1,"built":1,"into":2,"hillside":1,"for":1,"excellent":1,"natural":1,"acoustics":1,"epidaurus":1,"key":1,"areas":1,"orchestra":1,"round":1,"dancing":1,"place":1,"where":1,"chorus":7,"skene":2,"backdrop":1,"building":1,"origin":1,"word":1,"scene":2,"theatron":1,"seating":1,"group":1,"performers":2,"who":1,"sang":1,"chanted":1,"moved":1,"together":1,"commenting":1,"action":1,"representing":1,"community":2,"guiding":1,"audience":2,"response":1,"was":6,"central":2,"not":2,"decorative":1,"masks":6,"actors":2,"wore":1,"show":1,"character":1,"type":2,"emotion":1,"help":1,"project":1,"voice":2,"few":2,"male":2,"played":2,"all":1,"roles":2,"changing":1,"switch":1,"characters":3,"genres":1,"tragedy":6,"comedy":5,"dealt":1,"with":1,"serious":1,"themes":1,"fate":1,"downfall":1,"humorous":1,"often":1,"satirised":1,"politics":1,"society":1,"major":1,"playwrights":1,"accurate":1,"playwright":1,"notable":1,"works":1,"aeschylus":1,"three":2,"great":1,"tragedians":1,"added":2,"second":1,"actor":3,"oresteia":1,"prometheus":1,"bound":1,"sophocles":1,"third":1,"painting":1,"antigone":1,"oedipus":1,"rex":1,"electra":1,"euripides":1,"more":1,"realistic":2,"questioning":1,"medea":1,"bacchae":1,"aristophanes":1,"old":1,"political":1,"satire":1,"lysistrata":1,"frogs":1,"clouds":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"live":1,"commentary":1,"track":1,"crowd":1,"rolled":1,"one":1,"telling":1,"how":1,"feel":1,"filling":1,"story":1,"why":3,"matters":1,"gave":1,"script":1,"much":1,"dramatic":1,"structure":1,"common":1,"misconceptions":1,"had":1,"elaborate":1,"sets":1,"correction":3,"staging":1,"minimal":1,"devices":1,"meaning":1,"came":1,"language":1,"imagination":1,"detailed":1,"scenery":1,"just":1,"background":1,"decoration":1,"storytelling":1,"device":1,"narrated":1,"judged":1,"questioned":1,"voiced":1,"women":1,"stage":1,"men":1,"female":1,"using":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"describe":1,"role":1,"analyse":1,"useful":1,"interpret":1,"linked":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_5048434d3748476c76','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Ancient Roman Theatre (c. 3rd century BCE onward)','**Definition.** Roman theatre grew largely by **adapting Greek models** but shifted toward **broad entertainment and spectacle** for mass audiences.

**Conventions and features.**
- **Adaptation:** Romans borrowed Greek plots, characters, and forms, reworking them for Roman tastes and language (Latin).
- **Spectacle:** Emphasis on **entertainment** — comedy, farce, music, and, in the wider Roman world, large-scale spectacles. Roman theatres were often **free-standing stone buildings** (not dug into hillsides like Greek ones).
- **Playwrights:** **Plautus** (comedies full of stock characters, mistaken identity, and wordplay, e.g., *Miles Gloriosus*) and **Terence** (more refined comedies). **Seneca** wrote influential tragedies later admired in the Renaissance.

**Analogy.** If Greek theatre was a solemn civic-religious ceremony, Roman theatre leaned more toward a crowd-pleasing show — closer to popular entertainment.

**Why it matters.** Roman comedy''s **stock characters** and comic devices influenced later European comedy (including *commedia dell''arte* and Shakespeare).

**Common misconception.** *"Roman theatre was completely original and unrelated to Greek theatre."*
**Correction.** Roman theatre was heavily **based on Greek theatre**, then adapted for spectacle and Roman audiences.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* one way Roman theatre differed from Greek theatre.
- *Describe* the kind of plays Plautus wrote.
- *Analyse* why "spectacle" became more important in Roman performance.

---','{"concept":1,"ancient":1,"roman":12,"theatre":10,"3rd":1,"century":1,"bce":1,"onward":1,"definition":1,"grew":1,"largely":1,"adapting":1,"greek":7,"models":1,"but":1,"shifted":1,"toward":2,"broad":1,"entertainment":3,"and":11,"spectacle":4,"for":3,"mass":1,"audiences":2,"conventions":1,"features":1,"adaptation":1,"romans":1,"borrowed":1,"plots":1,"characters":3,"forms":1,"reworking":1,"them":1,"tastes":1,"language":1,"latin":1,"emphasis":1,"comedy":3,"farce":1,"music":1,"the":3,"wider":1,"world":1,"large":1,"scale":1,"spectacles":1,"theatres":1,"were":1,"often":1,"free":1,"standing":1,"stone":1,"buildings":1,"not":1,"dug":1,"into":1,"hillsides":1,"like":1,"ones":1,"playwrights":1,"plautus":2,"comedies":2,"full":1,"stock":2,"mistaken":1,"identity":1,"wordplay":1,"miles":1,"gloriosus":1,"terence":1,"more":3,"refined":1,"seneca":1,"wrote":2,"influential":1,"tragedies":1,"later":2,"admired":1,"renaissance":1,"analogy":1,"was":3,"solemn":1,"civic":1,"religious":1,"ceremony":1,"leaned":1,"crowd":1,"pleasing":1,"show":1,"closer":1,"popular":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"comic":1,"devices":1,"influenced":1,"european":1,"including":1,"commedia":1,"dell":1,"arte":1,"shakespeare":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"completely":1,"original":1,"unrelated":1,"correction":1,"heavily":1,"based":1,"then":1,"adapted":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"one":1,"way":1,"differed":1,"from":1,"describe":1,"kind":1,"plays":1,"analyse":1,"became":1,"important":1,"performance":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_be668f45f99431d29e','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: The Theatre History Timeline (Overview)','**Definition.** A big-picture map of how Western theatre evolved. Grade 7 works at **overview level** — knowing the order and one or two features of each era.

| Era | Approx. period | Key features | A name to know |
|-----|----------------|--------------|----------------|
| **Ancient Greek** | c. 550–350 BCE | Festivals of Dionysus; amphitheatres; chorus; masks; tragedy & comedy | Sophocles |
| **Ancient Roman** | c. 240 BCE–500 CE | Adapted Greek forms; spectacle; stone theatres; stock-character comedy | Plautus |
| **Medieval** | c. 500–1500 CE | Religious drama — **mystery, miracle, and morality plays**; travelling players | Guild "cycle" plays |
| **Renaissance / Shakespeare** | c. 1500–1650 | Rebirth of classical ideas; professional playhouses (e.g., the **Globe**); rich language | **William Shakespeare** |
| **Modern** | c. 1850–present | Realism, musicals, experimental & physical theatre, world theatre traditions | Stanislavski (acting), modern musicals |

**Analogy.** The timeline is like a family tree — each era inherits traits from its ancestors and passes new ones on.

**Why it matters.** Placing a play in time helps explain its style, staging, and purpose.

**Common misconception.** *"Shakespeare invented theatre."*
**Correction.** Shakespeare (Renaissance, ~1564–1616) came **almost 2,000 years after** Greek theatre began. He built on a very long tradition.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* the five eras of theatre in order.
- *Describe* one feature of medieval theatre.
- *Analyse* how Greek conventions can still be seen in later theatre.

---','{"240":1,"350":1,"500":2,"550":1,"1500":2,"1564":1,"1616":1,"1650":1,"1850":1,"concept":1,"the":5,"theatre":9,"history":1,"timeline":2,"overview":2,"definition":1,"big":1,"picture":1,"map":1,"how":2,"western":1,"evolved":1,"grade":1,"works":1,"level":1,"knowing":1,"order":2,"and":4,"one":2,"two":1,"features":2,"each":2,"era":3,"approx":1,"period":1,"key":1,"name":1,"know":1,"ancient":2,"greek":4,"bce":2,"festivals":1,"dionysus":1,"amphitheatres":1,"chorus":1,"masks":1,"tragedy":1,"comedy":2,"sophocles":1,"roman":1,"adapted":1,"forms":1,"spectacle":1,"stone":1,"theatres":1,"stock":1,"character":1,"plautus":1,"medieval":2,"religious":1,"drama":1,"mystery":1,"miracle":1,"morality":1,"plays":2,"travelling":1,"players":1,"guild":1,"cycle":1,"renaissance":2,"shakespeare":4,"rebirth":1,"classical":1,"ideas":1,"professional":1,"playhouses":1,"globe":1,"rich":1,"language":1,"william":1,"modern":2,"present":1,"realism":1,"musicals":2,"experimental":1,"physical":1,"world":1,"traditions":1,"stanislavski":1,"acting":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"family":1,"tree":1,"inherits":1,"traits":1,"from":1,"its":2,"ancestors":1,"passes":1,"new":1,"ones":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"placing":1,"play":1,"time":1,"helps":1,"explain":1,"style":1,"staging":1,"purpose":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"invented":1,"correction":1,"came":1,"almost":1,"000":1,"years":1,"after":1,"began":1,"built":1,"very":1,"long":1,"tradition":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"five":1,"eras":1,"describe":1,"feature":1,"analyse":1,"conventions":1,"can":1,"still":1,"seen":1,"later":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_3cc259bd0150d4f4d8','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Theatre Vocabulary Glossary','| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| **Amphitheatre** | Large open-air, semi-circular Greek theatre built into a hillside. |
| **Antagonist** | The character or force opposing the protagonist. |
| **Audience** | The people watching a live performance. |
| **Backstage** | Areas the audience cannot see, behind/around the stage. |
| **Blocking** | The planned movement and positioning of actors. |
| **Cast** | The group of actors in a production. |
| **Character** | A fictional person in the drama, with motives and traits. |
| **Chorus** | A group of Greek performers who sang, moved, and commented on the action. |
| **Climax** | The turning point of highest tension in a plot. |
| **Comedy** | A genre with humour and (usually) a happy outcome. |
| **Costume** | Clothing worn to show character or period. |
| **Cue** | A signal (line, sound, action) to trigger the next thing. |
| **Dénouement / Resolution** | The final stage where conflict is settled. |
| **Dialogue** | Spoken exchange between two or more characters. |
| **Director** | The person guiding the artistic vision of a production. |
| **Downstage** | The stage area closest to the audience. |
| **Exposition** | Opening stage that sets up characters and situation. |
| **Genre** | A category/type of theatre (tragedy, comedy, mime, musical). |
| **Improvisation** | Unscripted, spontaneously created performance. |
| **Mime** | Wordless storytelling through gesture and movement. |
| **Monologue** | A long speech by a single character. |
| **Orchestra** | The round "dancing place" for the chorus in a Greek theatre. |
| **Physical theatre** | Theatre making meaning mainly through the body. |
| **Plot** | The ordered arrangement of events in a drama. |
| **Props** | Movable objects handled by actors. |
| **Protagonist** | The main character the story follows. |
| **Puppetry** | Animating objects/puppets to perform. |
| **Rising action** | The build-up of conflict toward the climax. |
| **Script** | The written text: dialogue plus stage directions. |
| **Set** | Constructed scenery showing the location. |
| **Skene** | The backdrop building in a Greek theatre (origin of "scene"). |
| **Stage** | The area where performance happens. |
| **Stage left / right** | Left/right from the actor''s viewpoint facing the audience. |
| **Theatron** | Greek seating area; root of the word "theatre." |
| **Theme** | The central idea, message, or question a piece explores. |
| **Tragedy** | A serious genre dealing with downfall, fate, and grave themes. |
| **Upstage** | The stage area furthest from the audience. |
| **Wings** | Hidden offstage side areas where actors wait to enter. |

